- Your Name
- Your role at AAPS (family member, staff, scholar?)
- Ingredients, amounts, and directions for your recipe.

*****UPDATE****
9:18 AM

It appears the issue has been resolved, and scholars are now able to access and participate in scheduled class meetings via the Zoom app, which is installed on district devices. Instruction will resume effective immediately. Please help ensure that your scholar logs on as soon as possible.
_________________________

Families,

Earlier this morning, we started to receive error messages on Zoom as our instructional staff was logging into the platform for final preparation for today‚Äôs instruction. Zoom has put out a statement that this issue is a system-wide error and it appears as if they are working on a fix as quickly as possible.

For now, unfortunately, your scholar will not be able to access Zoom meetings until the issue is resolved. We are hoping Zoom will have this fixed shortly and are also exploring some back-up options for instruction.

We will be in touch again later with more information as we have it as we hope we can re-start instruction as soon as possible.

Thank you for your flexibility and patience.

Best,
Austin Achieve

post_text:
Tune in to our Facebook TOMORROW, Monday, August 3 at 6:00 p.m. as Austin Achieve Elementary School teacher, Miss Tibbetts, reads "Mae Among the Stars" by Roda Ahmed!

About the book: When Little Mae was a child, she dreamed of dancing in space. She imagined herself surrounded by billions of stars, floating, gliding, and discovering.

She wanted to be an astronaut.

Her mom told her, "If you believe it, and work hard for it, anything is possible.‚Äù

Little Mae‚Äôs curiosity, intelligence, and determination, matched with her parents' encouraging words, paved the way for her incredible success at NASA as the first African American woman to travel in space.

This book will inspire other young girls to reach for the stars, to aspire for the impossible, and to persist with childlike imagination.

shared_text:
Council Member Natasha Harper-Madison was live.
July 15 at 11:31 PM ¬∑

The COVID-19 surge is casting uncertainty on the coming school year in Austin as infections rise and health officials issue new guidance and directives. On this edition of "Talk with 'Tasha," I caught up with officials from AISD as well as Austin Achieve Public Schools, a charter system with two campuses in District 1. I also touched base with two teachers to find out their highly critical boots-on-the-ground perspective.

Guests include:

- Ali Ghilarducci, Supervisor for Community Engagement and External Communications, AISD

- John Armbrust, Founder and Executive Director, Austin Achieve Public Schools

- Mardi Nott, Teacher, Austin High School

- Antoine Thompson, Jr., Teacher/Coach, LBJ Early College High School

Tune in to our Facebook this Thursday at 6:00 p.m. as Austin Achieve Elementary School teacher, Miss Drum, reads "The Colors of Us" by Karen Katz!

About "The Colors of Us": Seven-year-old Lena is going to paint a picture of herself. She wants to use brown paint for her skin. But when she and her mother take a walk through the neighborhood, Lena learns that brown comes in many different shades. Through the eyes of a little girl who begins to see her familiar world in a new way, this book celebrates the differences and similarities that connect all people.

post_text:
Dear Austin Achieve Families,

Last week, we shared some initial information about our school reopening plans. This week, we received overdue, yet necessary guidance from the Texas EducationAgency (TEA). The guidance released presented us with some unforeseen regulations that we are now working through. Additionally, the number of confirmed COVID-19 cases here locally is rapidly increasing. In light of these facts, we are re-evaluating our initial reopening plans and have decided to postpone the start of the school year until Monday, August 17, 2020. This additional time will allow us to make needed adjustments to our instructional plans while ensuring we have the best systems and infrastructure to safely serve our community.

Our top priority has and always will be our community's health and well-being. We are committed to providing the highest quality of learning in the safest environment possible.

To read the full update, please click here: https://docdro.id/4sxFy6V

The P-EBT application deadline has been extended to July 31, 2020

P-EBT is a one-time benefit of $285 per eligible child and can be used in the same way as Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program food benefits to pay for groceries. P-EBT is for children who received SNAP in March 2020 and children who attended a school that offered free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 school year. If your child is eligible, apply at yourtexasbenefits.com/Learn/PEBT.

For more information, please contact 833-613-6220 or visit hhs.texas.gov/PEBT.

post_text:
The events of the past few weeks have been extremely difficult to witness. Amid the global pandemic, we are also experiencing another crisis - police brutality, racism, and violence towards the Black community.

The systemic racism that the Black community faces is not a new issue, and we must continue to stand against racism in all its forms. In times like these, to be silent is to be complicit. As educators, we have a duty to speak up, listen, and act -- and we will.

To our Black scholars, Black educators, and the entire Black community, you are loved, you are seen, and you matter.

post_text:
Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application instructions from schools in late May. The P-EBT application will open the first week of June.

P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more information, visit: hhs.texas.gov/PEBT

This #TeacherAppreciationTuesday, meet Austin Achieve Elementary teacher, Josephine Bingler.

Her favorite part of working at Austin Achieve is working alongside teachers who will do anything in their power to ensure success for all scholars and their path to college. Her fellow elementary teachers inspire her and push her to be the best teacher possible.

Fun fact: Before Ms. Bingler taught at Austin Achieve, she lived and taught in Guatemala for three years, where she learned to speak Spanish, how to make tortillas, and climbed 5 volcanoes!

Today is #GivingTuesdayNow! half Helen is joining together with our community partners to share a little happiness and brighten up timelines.

A global threat like COVID-19 affects everyone and presents an opportunity for us to come together as a community. While we have had to take a step back from providing treatment to students, we are doing our best to prepare for the upcoming school year and develop a plan of action to provide the best quality care to students in need.

Want to help spread half Helen‚Äôs message? Grab your glasses, snap a fun selfie, and share it in the comments.

üì¢ COVID-19 RESOURCES:
Rent Assitance Program:
To help Austinites at risk of losing their rental housing due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the City of Austin Government has put together a one-time Relief of Emergency Needs for Tenants (RENT) rent assistance program lottery. Please follow this link to learn more about eligibility requirements, how to apply and more. http://austintexas.gov/rent

Relief in State of Emergency (RISE) Fund:
If you or your family did not qualify for a federal stimulus check, a fund has been up to help Austinites in need during these trying times. Please follow this link to learn more about the different non-profits granting funds. Eligibility requirements and application details vary by non-profit. https://www.kut.org/post/austin-created-15-million-pandemic-relief-fund-heres-how-access-some-money

For more information on food/health/financial resources during COVID-19, visit bit.ly/AAPSDistanceLearningHub or austinachieve.org/coronavirus.

post_text:
It's #TeacherAppreciationTuesday! Meet Hannah Temple, our high school Visual and Performing Arts teacher.

Mrs. Temple has been part of the Austin Achieve family for six years. To her, AAPS is a place where you can be yourself no matter who you are or where you come from. In her own words, "As soon as I walk through those double doors each morning, I know I'm home."

She can't wait to see her artists working in the art studio again and for the exciting opportunities they'll have lined up next year.

Fun fact: Mrs. Temple is a 5th-generation Austinite (making her daughter 6th generation!)! She has lots of love and pride for our city and community. #WeAreAchieve

üì¢ If you are in need of food, there are two Mobile Food Pantries in Austin this week! These pantries are open to all during the COVID-19 outbreak. Every family receives a large box of non-perishable groceries, including frozen meat.

Families can pick up for other families and/or for senior neighbors who are unable to attend on their own by providing a signed note that includes the other person's name, the pick-up person's name, a statement that the senior/other family is appointing them to be their proxy, their signature, and the date.

Friday, April 3
Shoreline Church | 15201 Burnet Rd, Austin, TX 78728
10:30 a.m. - 12 p.m.

Saturday, April 4
Cedar Creek Middle School | 125 Voss Pkwy
Cedar Creek, Texas, 78612
9:00 a.m. - 10:00 a.m.

"Women belong in all places where decisions are being made." -Ruth Bader Ginsburg

To support Austin Achieve's alumni on their college journey, visit: https://www.amplifyatx.org/organizations/austin-achieve

post_text:
This #AmplifyAustin, join us in our mission to provide a college-ready education for all scholars.

We are committed to providing our scholars with a rigorous academic program that prepares scholars for the demands of college-level courses and success in the global economy. To ensure that our scholars have the foundational skills to succeed in an increasingly STEM-focused job market, our curriculum emphasizes computer science. As early as Kindergarten, scholars are introduced to coding and will graduate having mastered at least one coding language. A gift of $50 can support the technology and curriculum resources necessary for scholars to succeed in CS courses. #AllScholarsCollegeReady

To support Austin Achieve‚Äôs STEM courses, visit: https://www.amplifyatx.org/organizations/austin-achieve

This #AmplifyAustin, join us in our mission to provide a college-ready education for all scholars.

Every high school scholar participates in our 4-year College Seminar Program, designed to provide scholars with the skills, information and resources they will need to succeed in college and beyond. A cornerstone of this program is the annual college campus visits, which provide prospective students with a first-hand look at universities in Texas and out of state. A gift of $100 can provide a college-bound scholar with the opportunity to visit prospective campuses. #AllScholarsCollegeReady

To help Austin Achieve‚Äôs high school scholars attend college visits, visit: https://www.amplifyatx.org/organizations/austin-achieve

Parents of 11th graders: Want to help your scholar pay for college? File your taxes!

Austin Achieve High School is hosting a Tax Night on Wednesday 3/4 from 5:30-6:45pm at the High School Cafeteria.

If you've never filed taxes before, or aren't even sure if you can file, this night is for you! Come learn about how to file your taxes and how filing can help you earn up to $6,000 per year for your child's college education.

post_text:
Meet Pre-K Teacher, Terri Davis! For Ms. Davis, #BlackHistoryMonth is a 365-day journey, not just a month-long celebration.

Ms. Davis is proud to be an educator and hopes that by sharing Black history with her scholars, they will grow to appreciate the culture even more. She herself was inspired to teach thanks to the Black educators who influenced her from her elementary through high school years.

She was especially influenced by her parents, Nathaniel and Barbara, who instilled within her the values of family, spirituality, and cultural pride.

post_text:
Meet Austin Achieve High School's Principal, Mackee Mason!

As a School Leader, Mr. Mason works to ensure that our scholars learn about Black Americans who have had an impact on our country year round - not just during #BlackHistoryMonth. He believes that when scholars of color see educators that look like them, they raise expectations for themselves and believe in their own power to achieve what their teachers have.

Mr. Mason is inspired by former President Barack Obama for his prioritization of education as a tool for success, as well as countless other influential Black leaders. In his own words, ‚ÄúWe stand on the shoulders of our ancestors that laid the groundwork for us to succeed.‚Äù

post_text:
Meet Deandre Greer, Special Education Paraprofessional at Austin Achieve Middle School!

For Mr. Greer, #BlackHistoryMonth means the joy of being able to see people with the same skin tone as himself breaking barriers and inspiring power within himself.

He's proud to be an educator, leader, and advocate for his scholars, reminding them to love who they are and continue pushing towards excellence.

Mr. Greer is inspired by influential black leaders such as former President Barack Obama. #BlackHistoryMonth #WeAreAchieve

post_text:
Meet Austin Achieve staff member, Breanna Wyrick! Breanna is part of the Information Technology team, working her magic behind the scenes to keep our campus connected and troubleshoot technology issues. #BlackHistoryMonth

She understands how important it is for scholars of color to see Black educators and staff on campus, because having someone that comes from the same background helps scholars feel more welcomed and understood. In her own words, "Black kids should be able to see themselves in the very people that are helping shape their minds as they grow and develop."

Breanna is inspired by influential and successful Black women such as Beyonce, Serena Williams, and Michelle Obama.

Meet first-generation college graduate and 8th-grade Reading Teacher, Sabra Lawson! She received her Bachelor's Degree from The University of Texas at Austin in 2015. #FirstGenFriday

After graduating from high school, Ms. Lawson joined the workforce but ultimately realized that a college degree was necessary to achieve her long-term career goals. At 23, Ms. Lawson began her education at Austin Community College District and transferred to UT Austin.

Ms. Lawson's advice to other first-gen scholars at Austin Achieve is, "Earn the respect of your peers and professors. They will become your network and can connect you to opportunities you might never expect. And apply for every scholarship you can find!" #WeAreAchieve

post_text:
Meet Austin Achieve Board Member and Past Board Chair, Andy Greenawalt! #SchoolBoardAppreciationMonth

Mr. Greenawalt was born into a family of educators and his love for education runs deep. After a successful career at Dell, he retired in 2000 and feels privileged to support Austin Achieve‚Äôs mission during this phase in his life.

Mr. Greenawalt strongly believes that by providing a choice for where parents can send their children to school, we can provide an equal opportunity where it hasn‚Äôt traditionally existed. His greatest sense of fulfillment as a board member comes from seeing the joy of our scholars as they unlock their own potential and gain the confidence to find their rightful place in the world.

When Mr. Greenawalt isn‚Äôt supporting Austin Achieve‚Äôs mission, you can find him staying active by cycling, golfing, and skiing; attending jazz concerts with his wife; or vacationing in the mountains of Breckenridge, Colorado. #WeAreAchieve

post_text:
This #FirstGenFriday, we're highlighting middle school science teacher, Shawna Echebelem! Ms. Echebelem earned her Bachelor's degree in Psychology from Grand Valley State University in 2005.

Ms. Echebelem knew she wanted to attend college from a young age, thanks to encouragement and support from her family. Balancing two jobs and a full course load while attending college, she learned how to prioritize when things got tough.

To other first-generation scholars, Ms. Echebelem shared this encouragement: "Never lose faith in yourself. Walking an unbeaten path can be overwhelming, but the feeling that comes when you walk across the stage after you've earned your degree is worth it." #WeAreAchieve

This #TeacherAppreciationTuesday, we're introducing high school math teacher, Claire Fritz.

For Ms. Fritz, the best part of teaching at Austin Achieve is the amount of professional growth she‚Äôs experienced. Every day, she feels that she grows into a stronger educator, and attributes that growth to the strength of our organization. Though teaching can be challenging, Ms. Fritz says it is worth it when she witnesses scholars growing one step closer to achieving their dreams.

Ms. Fritz has taught the junior class of 2021 for five years - since they were in 7th grade. In her own words, ‚ÄúI feel so lucky to have gotten the opportunity to see them grow into the amazing young adults they are today over the years. I am so proud of them.‚Äù #WeAreAchieve

This #TeacherAppreciationTuesday, we're highlighting elementary teacher, Mark Rogers!

Mr. Rogers loves working at Austin Achieve with colleagues across all departments who are so great at what they do. He does this work for the reward of seeing his scholars grow over time through 'looping' (teaching one group of scholars from one grade to the next).

When Mr. Rogers is not teaching, you can find him spending time with his two young sons. Fun fact: Mr. Rogers only speaks in Spanish to his sons so they can learn a second language! #WeAreAchieve

post_text:
This #FirstGenFriday, we're highlighting 7th grade science teacher Stephanie Lara.

Ms. Lara received her Bachelor of Fine Arts from the University of Texas at Austin in 2013. Coming from a family of migrant workers, Ms. Lara's parents encouraged her to pursue higher education as a path to success. Though she faced challenges along the way, she persevered and utilized her time in college as a growing experience.

Ms. Lara shared the following advice to other first-gen scholars: ‚ÄúAsk for help when you need it, get to know your professors, and get involved on campus. Experience as much as you can!‚Äù

This #StaffAppreciationTuesday, we're highlighting Development Director, Celina Maggi!

Celina's favorite part of working at Austin Achieve is meeting our scholars, and she feels honored to share their stories with Austin Achieve's supporters. As a first-generation college student, she knows firsthand the profound impact education can have on scholars‚Äô lives and believes everyone should have access to exemplary education as a pathway to leading a more fulfilling life.

When she‚Äôs not working, you can find her hiking, hitting up dog parks, or relaxing on the couch with her three dogs, Olive, Ethel, and Otis.

post_text:
This #StaffAppreciationTuesday, we‚Äôre highlighting Jessica Herrera, who works in Austin Achieve‚Äôs Family & Community Engagement Department.

Jessica‚Äôs favorite thing about working for Austin Achieve is hearing stories about why parents choose our school. She loves meeting different families and helping them find the best fit for their scholars, aligning with her long-term goal of becoming a Licensed Marriage and Family Therapist. Her life's mission is to work with families, especially children, in order to help build a more cohesive family unit where advocating for oneself is empowering and not fearful. #WeAreAchieve

post_text:
This #FirstGenFriday, we're highlighting 5th-grade science teacher, Corey Jones!

Mr. Jones earned his Bachelor‚Äôs of Science from Texas Lutheran University in 2011. From childhood, he knew that a college education was pivotal to a successful future, so he worked hard to get there. As the first in his family to attend college, he wanted to set an expectation for those who would follow after him, including his children.

For the first-generation college scholars at Austin Achieve, Mr. Jones shared this advice: ‚ÄúTake your ‚Äòright now‚Äô seriously. Work hard, strive for excellence, and apply for as many scholarships as you can.‚Äù
